      <hedline>
        <hl1>Metro Business; No Refunds From Con Ed</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Joseph P. Fried</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Fried, Joseph P</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Federal District Court Judge Lawrence E Kahn rules that Consolidated Edison does not have to refund more than $100 million it charged customers after accident at Indian Point 2 nuclear power plant; says New York State law requiring refunds violates Con Ed's constitutional rights (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>A federal judge has ruled that Consolidated Edison does not have to refund more than $100 million it charged customers after an accident at a generating plant.</p>
        <p>The judge, Lawrence E. Kahn of Federal District Court in Albany, ruled Tuesday that a state law requiring the refunds violated Con Ed's constitutional rights because it ''legislatively determines guilt and inflicts punishment'' on the company without a trial in court.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>A federal judge has ruled that Consolidated Edison does not have to refund more than $100 million it charged customers after an accident at a generating plant.</p>
        <p>The judge, Lawrence E. Kahn of Federal District Court in Albany, ruled Tuesday that a state law requiring the refunds violated Con Ed's constitutional rights because it ''legislatively determines guilt and inflicts punishment'' on the company without a trial in court.</p>
        <p>A spokesman for Gov. George E. Pataki, who approved the law in August, said yesterday that the state would appeal the decision. The refunds were intended to make up for higher charges customers paid the utility for replacement power after an accident in February shut down the Indian Point 2 nuclear-powered generating plant in Westchester County.</p>
        <p>Joseph P. Fried (NYT)</p>
      </block>
